    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P05 and P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full available series. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window: 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 through 2021-03-04 22:30:00+08:00 (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in that window, detect anomalies as points where value >= global P95 (high) or value <= global P05 (low). Produce a compact table (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, direction (high/low), anomaly_count (number of anomalous rows in window), earliest_anomaly_ts (first anomalous timestamp in window), extremum_value (max value for high, min value for low), global_p95, global_p05, severity_ratio (for high = extremum_value/global_p95; for low = global_p05/extremum_value). Sort by severity_ratio descending and return top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step produced a compact anomaly_summary (stored in kernel as anomalies_summary) showing many single-point spikes across components in the 22:00–22:30 window. Top severity ratios point to: (1) very large 'low' deviations on Tomcat02 (22:24) and Tomcat04 (22:17); (2) multiple 'high' disk and MySQL resource spikes around 22:00–22:13 (Mysql01/Mysql02 and IG02). We still must (A) identify which anomaly groups correspond to the two reported failures (cluster by occurrence time), (B) confirm faults (consecutive anomalies vs isolated spikes) and filter noise, and (C) if multiple same-level services are flagged, use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service. No trace-based localization has been done yet. The next step is to group anomalies by their earliest occurrence timestamp to find the main incident times and list anomaly details for the top timestamps so we can decide which two timestamps correspond to the two reported failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the anomalies_summary DataFrame already in the kernel, do two things (keep outputs compact):\n1) Aggregate anomalies_summary by earliest_anomaly_ts (minute precision) and compute: anomaly_series_count (number of anomaly series at that timestamp), distinct_components_count, and list the top 10 timestamps sorted by anomaly_series_count descending. Return columns: earliest_anomaly_ts, anomaly_series_count, distinct_components_count.\n2) For the top 2 timestamps from step 1, return up to 20 anomaly rows (from anomalies_summary) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, direction, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, extremum_value, global_p95, global_p05, severity_ratio. Sort these rows by severity_ratio descending.\nStore results in kernel variables but only print the compact tables requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies by minute and inspected the top timestamps. Key findings so far: (1) the busiest anomaly minute is 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 (6 anomaly series) affecting Mysql02 (multiple local-disk I/O and MySQL thread/handler spikes) and IG02 (high CPU WIO). These show the largest deviations and are strong candidates for one failure around 22:00. (2) Other notable anomaly minutes: 22:10:00+08:00 (IG02 large sda read spike) and two very high-severity 'low' anomalies on Tomcat nodes: Tomcat04 at 22:17:00+08:00 and Tomcat02 at 22:24:00+08:00 (these were single-point but extreme drops in CPU idle/CPU util). At this stage we cannot yet assert which two of these anomaly clusters correspond to the two reported failures. To localize root cause components and confirm propagation, we must consult traces (to find downstream service impact/latency or row_count drops around candidate minutes) and logs (if any). Trace and log inspection should focus on the candidate minutes and candidate components: Mysql02, IG02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, and MG01/docker services that mediate traffic. No useful aggregated logs were returned earlier, but we should still query raw trace rows in the incident minutes to detect latency/row_count anomalies that correlate with metric faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, return all rows (compact) for the UTC+8 minutes: 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00, 2021-03-04 22:10:00+08:00, 2021-03-04 22:17:00+08:00, and 2021-03-04 22:24:00+08:00. Restrict cmdb_id to this set: [\"Mysql02\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"dockerA1\",\"dockerA2\",\"dockerB2\"]. For each returned row show columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Also produce a small aggregate that for each (timestamp, cmdb_id) counts how many trace series were present at that minute. Limit printed rows to 200 total and sort by timestamp then cmdb_id."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metric anomalies and then fetched trace rows at candidate minutes. Findings so far: (1) The largest anomaly cluster is at 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 affecting Mysql02 (multiple local-disk I/O spikes and MySQL Threads/Handler metrics) and IG02 (high CPU WIO). These metrics show strong deviations (severity ratios 3–6), suggesting an IO/DB-host issue at ~22:00. (2) IG02 again shows a very large local-disk read spike at 22:10:00+08:00. (3) There are two extreme single-point 'low' anomalies on Tomcat nodes: Tomcat04 at 22:17:00+08:00 (CPU util drop) and Tomcat02 at 22:24:00+08:00 (CPU idle very low), which are high-severity but isolated. (4) Trace rows for the candidate minutes were returned: at 22:00 many components have full trace coverage (MG01: 30 series, Tomcat02: 18 series, IG02: 15 series, Tomcat04: 15 series), and at 22:24 many docker services and Tomcat nodes have many series. This indicates we can localize impact via traces. What remains: correlate metric faults to service-level impact using trace metrics across the entire incident window (22:00–22:30) to (A) confirm which anomaly groups correspond to the two reported failures, (B) determine exact occurrence minute for each failure (first point of a consecutive fault), and (C) identify the most likely root cause component using downstream trace impact. Logs did not show aggregated results earlier, so trace analysis is the next priority.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, for the components [\"Mysql02\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"dockerA1\",\"dockerA2\",\"dockerB2\"] and timestamps within 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 through 2021-03-04 22:30:00+08:00 (inclusive), filter rows where trace_name is one of: [\"trace.self.duration_mean\",\"trace.self.duration_p95\",\"trace.self.row_count\"]. Produce two compact outputs (keep total printed rows <= 200):\n1) Aggregate table grouped by (cmdb_id, trace_name) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, min_ts, max_ts, min_value, max_value, ts_of_min_value, ts_of_max_value. Return all groups (sorted by cmdb_id then trace_name).\n2) Up to 100 raw rows of the filtered trace records sorted by timestamp then cmdb_id showing columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. \nStore results in kernel variables and print only these two compact tables." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metric anomalies and traced activity across candidate minutes. Key findings so far: (1) A concentrated anomaly cluster at 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 affecting Mysql02 (multiple local-disk I/O spikes and MySQL Threads/Handler metrics) and IG02 (high CPU WIO). These metrics are the strongest candidates for one failure near 22:00. (2) IG02 shows another large disk read spike at 22:10. (3) Two very-high-severity but isolated 'low' anomalies on Tomcat nodes were observed: Tomcat04 at 22:17 (CPU util drop) and Tomcat02 at 22:24 (CPU idle drop). Trace coverage is dense across the window and we retrieved trace.self.row_count and trace.self.duration_mean groups for the relevant components covering 22:00–22:29. What remains: we must confirm which anomaly clusters correspond to the two reported failures and identify the root cause component for each by (A) checking whether service-level traces show downstream impact (increased latency or reduced row_count) that coincide with the metric anomalies, and (B) determining whether metric anomalies are isolated spikes or consecutive (fault) events. To do this we need a focused comparison of per-component trace metrics at the anomaly minutes versus their recent baseline. This will tell us which metric faults propagated to service-level behavior and thus indicate the root-cause component for each reported failure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, for components [\"Mysql02\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"dockerA1\",\"dockerA2\",\"dockerB2\"] and trace_names [\"trace.self.row_count\",\"trace.self.duration_mean\"], restrict to timestamps from 2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00 through 2021-03-04 22:30:00+08:00 (inclusive). For each combination (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute these compact outputs:\n1) The median value across the full 22:00–22:30 window (call median_window).\n2) For each target minute T in [2021-03-04 22:00:00+08:00, 2021-03-04 22:10:00+08:00, 2021-03-04 22:17:00+08:00, 2021-03-04 22:24:00+08:00], retrieve value at T (value_T) and value at the previous minute (value_prev = value at T - 1 minute). If a value is missing, mark as NaN.\n3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name, T) compute change_ratio = (value_T - median_window) / median_window if median_window != 0; otherwise set change_ratio = NaN and also provide absolute_diff = value_T - median_window.\nReturn a compact table (limit 200 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, T, value_prev, value_T, median_window, change_ratio, absolute_diff. Sort rows by abs(change_ratio) descending (treat NaN as lowest priority). Also produce a short aggregate that lists, for each T, how many (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs have |change_ratio| >= 0.5 or absolute_diff > 0 (for median_window == 0). Print only these two compact tables and store them in kernel variables for next steps."
}

Based on the metric anomalies (multiple LOCALDISK and MySQL KPI spikes) and trace correlation (service latency at 22:10 following IG02 disk activity), the most likely root causes are a Mysql02 disk I/O overload at 22:00 and an IG02 disk read spike causing IO wait and downstream latency at 22:10.

